http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/bangalore/%E2%80%98Encourage-films-don%E2%80%99t-interfere-in-creative-work%E2%80%99/article14025586.ece

It was amidst a galaxy of stars from the world of cinema that the eighth edition of Bengaluru International Film Festival (BIFFes) was inaugurated, with the Vidhana Soudha forming the backdrop.Befitting the venue, senior actor Jaya Bachchan, who inaugurated the event, had a word of advice for the political class. She urged them to encourage cinema, but not interfere in its creative pursuits.In a speech that came after that of Karnataka Chalanachitra Academy Chairperson S.V. Rajendra Singh Babu, who listed the sops offered by the Karnataka government to the industry, she directed her advice to Chief Minister Siddaramaiah, who shared the dais with her.“Creative people should have the freedom to think and act. Interference results in sub-standard work,” she said. “I am sure your government will not do that.” She said that she would persuade the Mumbai film industry to use the facilities in Karnataka.The Who’s Who of the Kannada film industry, including Shivarajkumar; Sanjay Leela Bhansali of Bajirao Mastani fame; Telugu star Venkatesh; and Hollywood producer Ashok Amritraj, were among those in attendance at the colourful event.